# Component Structure and Styling

## Atomic Design Pattern

Hydra uses the Atomic Design pattern to organize components:

- `atoms/`: Basic UI elements like buttons, input fields, charts, card structures
- `molecules/`: Combinations of atoms (e.g., StatCard, ChartCard)
- `organisms/`: Complete UI sections like tabs (DashboardTab, ProjectsTab)
- `templates/`: Components that define page layouts
- `pages/`: Components that compose final pages
- `layouts/`: Common layout components

## Chart Components

The application extensively uses chart components for data visualization:
- `HorizontalBarChart.tsx`: Horizontal bar charts for progress displays
- `StackedBarChart.tsx`: Stacked bar charts for issue distributions
- `BubbleChart.tsx`: Bubble charts for deadline status
- `AreaTrendChart.tsx`: Area charts for trend visualization
- `StatusDonutChart.tsx`: Donut charts for status distributions

## Card Components

Cards are used to display information in consistent containers:
- `StatCard.tsx`: Displays statistics with title, value, and change indicators
- `ChartCard.tsx`: Container for chart components with title and icon

## Styling Guide

- TailwindCSS for styling (inline classes)
- Dark mode support with `dark:` prefix classes
- UI components follow Radix UI and shadcn/ui patterns
- Conditional classes using `clsx` or `class-variance-authority`

## Component Implementation Patterns

- TypeScript interfaces for Props definition
- Functional components and React hooks
- Zustand for state management
- Event handlers use the `handle` prefix (e.g., `handleClick`)

## Language Guidelines

- All user-facing text must be in English
- Variables and component names should follow English naming conventions
- Comments can be written in Korean or English
- Use proper system UI language and terminology